               <function type="2">
                  <data version="0">
                     <name>isValidTypeString</name>
                     <description>Tests if the given string is a valid C++ type, returning true if it is valid. The only validation that is done is checking proper syntax since checking actual names is beyond the scope of this program.</description>
                     <static/>
                     <type>bool</type>
                     <return_description>True if the given string has valid syntax for a C++ type or false otherwise.</return_description>
                     <operation>If the given string does not match the basic syntax of a C++ type then return false.</operation>
                     <operation>Create a boolean _ret_ set to true and find all template argument matches within the given string saving matches to _matches_.</operation>
                     <operation>Iterate through all _matches_. If any match is not a valid C++ template argument then set _ret_ to false and stop iterating through all matches.</operation>
                     <operation>Return _ret_.</operation>
                  </data>
                  <variable type="1">
                     <data version="0">
                        <name>value</name>
                        <description>The string that is checked for valid C++ type syntax.</description>
                        <type>const QString&amp;</type>
                     </data>
                  </variable>
               </function>
               <function type="2">
                  <data version="0">
                     <name>isValidTemplateArgument</name>
                     <description>Tests if the given string is a valid C++ template argument for a C++ type, returning true if it is valid. The only validation that is done is checking proper syntax.</description>
                     <static/>
                     <type>bool</type>
                     <return_description>True if the given string has valid syntax for a C++ template argument or false otherwise.</return_description>
                     <operation>Initialize _ret_ to true, _arguments_ as the broken list of all arguments within the given string, nd _regexp_ as the regular expression engine for checking syntax.</operation>
                     <operation>Iterate through all arguments in _arguments_. If an argument fails its syntax check then set _ret_ to false and break out of the iteration. If the argument is valid and itself contains another template argument then recursively call this method to check it is also valid, setting _ret_ to false and breaking from iteration if it is not valid.</operation>
                     <operation>Return _ret_.</operation>
                  </data>
                  <variable type="1">
                     <data version="0">
                        <name>value</name>
                        <description>The string that is checked for valid C++ template argument syntax.</description>
                        <type>const QString&amp;</type>
                     </data>
                  </variable>
               </function>
